{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_gaston_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583954/1910073101/0448.xml":{"full_text":"7\nIn Selecting\nToilet Soap\nWhy not procure one possessing delicate emol-\nlient properties sufficient to allay minor irrita\n1 tions, remove redness and roughness, prevent\npore clogging, soften and soothe sensative con\nditions, and promote skin and scalp health gen\nrally? Such a soap, combined with the purest\nof saponaceous ingredients and most fragrant\nand refreshing of flower odors, is Cuticura\nSoap. It costs but a little more, it wears to a\nwafer, and gives comfort and satisfaction every\nmoment of its use in the toilet, bath and nur\nsery. No other soap has done so much for poor\ncomplexions, red, rough hands, and dry, thin\nand falling hair. It has done even more for\nakin-tortured and disfigured infants, children\nand adults, when assisted by Cuticura Oint\nment. As a toilet soap for preserving and pur-\nifying the complexion, hands and hair, and as\na skin soap for dissipating irritating and un\nsightly conditions of the skin, Cuticura Soa#\nhas no rivals worth mentioning. Its sale is\ngreater than the world\u2019s product of other skin\nsoaps oombined. It is sold wherever civiliza\ntion has penetrated. It has depots in all world\ncenters. For the thirty-two page Cuticura\nBooklet, a guide to the best care of the skin\nand hair, address Potter Drug Chemical Cor-\nporation, 131 Columbus Ave., Boston, U. S. A.\n\nPOLITICAL SITUATION SHOWS\nSOME SIGNS OF ACTIVITY\nBy HERVBY W. LAIRD\nMontgomery, July 30.\u2014(Special),\u2014With\nthe prospect that Joe Thompson, nomi\nnee of the republicans, may challenge\nEmmet O'Neal, the democratic nominee,\nfor a series of joint debates, the political\nsituation, dull Indeed since the primary,\nI Shows some signs of activity. In tho\nmeantime a campaign committee to take\nup the cause of the democrats Is ready\nfor what may offer, Chairman Jesse\nStallings and Secretary C. A. Beasley\nbeing in fighting form.\nReports from the \"bloody Seventh\" dls\nl trlct where M. W. Howard, author of\n\u201cIf Christ Came to Congress,\" is trying\nto beat the democratic \u2022nominee, John\nBurnett, for Congress, ar& encouraging\nfor Mr. purnett. N. M. Gallant, tax\ncollector of Etowah county, who was In\nMontgomery this week, stated that there\nneed be no fears. \u201cWe are going to send\n1 Mr. Burnett back all right.\" he stated.\n\u201cHe has made us a good man and there\nIs no llkllhood that Howard will be able\nto hurt him much.\u201d\nVery Enconraglng\nThis report Is regarded as very en\ncouraging. as there were many who\n\u25a0eemed to think that Burnett was going\nto have a great and a hard fight to\nnominee for governor on the democratic\nnominee for governor on the democratic\nticket, had already agred to give Mr.\nBurnett a few speches, as will the sev\neral members of Congress and the two\nsenators. The work of the new cam\npaign committee will be put In largely In\nthat section, and In helping out the\ndemocratic nominees In some of the\ndoubtful counties. The outlook of suc\ncess for Burnett Is so good that there\nceems no sort of danger that a solid\ndelegation will not remain In Congress.\nBrysUlMnu Seperated\nA great many people think they see\nIn the divided condition of the republU\ncan forces a chance to bvlng about a\ncondition of disturbance in the rank and\nfile and the opening for some of the\nmore conservative ones to lead. Taft Is\nknown to have stated on many occas\nions that he thought the people of a\nState ought to have a say in the officers\nto serve them. He has not approached\nthat line of action In making appoint\nments. but a great number have yet a\nhope that he wfll. If he should take\nthis view It is regarded as probable that\nhe will add to the confusion that now\nexists by refusing to say yes every time\nthe referees name a man for the place.\nTWO MEN ARRESTED\nON MURDER CHARGE\nGuntersvllle, July 30.\u2014(Special).\u2014Will\nWest and Emmltt Kearney, both white\nmen, were today arrested and lodged. In\njail on a charge of murder. The crime\nwith which they are charged is one of\nthe most shocking and cold blooded that\nwas ever committed In this county.\nA few weeks ago Will Stearnes, a\nnegro, was killed on B. H. Greenwood's\nfarm, one mile from Guntersvllle.\nStearnes had Just plowed out to the end\nof his last round for the day and was\nIn the act of taking out his team when\nhe was shot three times In the head\nfrom ambush and Instantly killed.\nStearnes was a quiet and hard working\nnegro and so far as Is known had never\nhad any trouble with anybody.\nWest was arrested on his father's farm\nfifteen miles from town and was lodged\nIn Jail about 12 o'clock today, and Kear\nney, who lives In town, was arrested and\nplaced In Jail almost immediately there\nafter. Both defendants were brought be\nfore Probate Judge Carter this after\nnoon and their preliminary trials were\nset for August 8.\nNew Warehouse Manager Elected\nMarlon, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014At a meet\ning of the Union Storage company, the\nFarmers' Warehouse company of Perry\ncounty, todiff, Capt. J. W, Smith resigned\nas manager on account of bad health.\nCaptain Smith has been In warehouse\nbusiness here for 20 years. Walter H.\nRyan, recently nominated for sheriff, was\nelected manager for the balance of this\nyear, Henry W. Ivey, one of the best\nknown young farmers east of the Cahaba\nriver, was elected as assistant manager,\nand will doubtless be promoted on the\nfirst of the new year. The warehouse has\nyielded the Farmers' union a handsome\nprofit since it was Incorporated two years\nago, and will be continued along progres\nsive lines.\nV-'.\nI Duffy\u2019s Pure Malt Whiskey\nMEDICINE FOR OLD AND YOUNG\n6 Large Bottles, $5.50\n12 Large Bottles, $10.00\nLarge Bottles. 43.80 i Large Bottle, |l.00\nShipped to any address, express prepaid, on receipt of order and price.\nDuffy's Pure Malt Whiskey must not bo regarded at ordinary commercial\nWhiskies. 'It 1* on.abgolutelyspure distillation of malted grain. Its palatablllty\nand Its freedom .from lpjlllrtius substances render it so Apt it can be retained\nhg the meet nengltlV* Utoniach. It has been the standard of purity for fifty\npear*. MV.'*-*\nIt Is invaluable for overworked men, dellcato women add sickly children,\nft strengthens and sustains-the system; is a piomoter of health and longevity;\nMakes the old feel young and keeps the young strong. It Is recognised as a\nj family medicine everywhere. You should have It In your home. It will do you\ngood.\nJt Is a wonderful remedy *n the treatment end cure of consumption, pneu\n1 Bonta, grippe, bronchitis, coughs, colds, asthma, malaria, low fevers, stomach\ngroupies and all wasting, ..weakened, diseased conditions. If taken as directed.\nRemit by express otdfer, postofflee order or certlded check to The Duffy Malt\nWhiskey Company. 3 White street, Rochester, N. Y. References: National Bank of\nCommerce, Lincoln National Bank, Rochester, N. Y\u201e Ddn's or Bradstrdet's\nAgency,\ne\n'V*'*\nSCHOOL CENSUS\nIS DISAPPOINTING\nIndicated Population of Selma\nNot More Than 15,000\nTO HOLD CORN FESTIVAL\nPlan to FInve Big Celebration In Dallas\nCounty This Fall\u2014Banner Corn\nCrop Is Expected\u2014Two\nChildren Die\nSelma, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014According to\nthe school census which has just been\ncompleted the report of the government\ncensus when It Is made public will prove\na source of disappointment to residents\nhere.\nThe majority of the citizens of Selma\nhave for some months past believed that\nthe population of the city would go to\nnew the 20.000 mark. But instead it is\nnow believed that the population of Selma\nwill fall several thousand short of that\nmark.\nThe school census, which has just been\ncompleted and which was carefully\ntaken shows that there are in Selma 3*)4\nschool children between the ages of 7 and\n21 years. The lowest average by which\nthis can be figured is at the rate of four\npersons to every child (and which would\nmake the population of Selma 13,616.\nAbout the highest average at which It can\nbe figured is 4V& to every child and which\nwould give the city a population of about\n17,020.\nIt is now believed that when the gov\nernment makes its report that there will\nbe found to be very little variance be\ntween it and the school census. These\nfigures will also show that during the\npast two years the population of Selma\nhas been on the decline lhstead of an in\ncrease. The last directory of Selma,\nwhich was compiled in 1909, gave the city\na population of 17,290. The extreme dull\ntimes and business depression following\nthe recent panic caused a large number\nof families to move from Selma. But\nwith the return of prosperity and the\nopening up of the industries here, families\nare beginning to move into Selma and it\nis believed that within less than a year\nthe population of the city will be nearly\n20,000.\nMay Hold Corn Festival\nA corn festival to celebrate the large\ncorn crop of this section may be held here\nduring the month of October if the plans\nof certain Selmlans can be put through.\nThe movement for the com festival was\nonly broached a few days ago, but since\nthen the project has grown in favor and\nthe majority of the business men of the\ncity are anxious to get up some kind\u00abof an\nentertainment for the people of this sec\ntion this fall.\nIf the corn festival in held here it will\nbe on the order of those held in the north\nwest and will perhaps be the first of its\nkind ever held in this state. More corn\nwill be raised and gathered in Central\nAlabama this fall than ever before, and\nthe celebration of this crop will be made\na big event with the fanners.\nNo organized movement for the holding\nof the festival has yet been launched, but\nit is believed that some definite steps will\nbe taken during the coming weeks. A\nmeeting of a number of citizens will no\ndoubt be held and plans for the holding of\nthe festival will be perfected.\nIf held the festival will be taken part\nin by nearly every farmer in Central Ala\nbama. Every citizen of Selma will work\nto make it a great success and the enter\ntainment would also encourage the far\nmers of this section also to raise each\nyear a larger crop of corn.\nDeath of Little Child\nThe two-year-old child of Mr. and Mrs.\nVirgil Rushing died at their home on Syc\namore street in the eastern part of the\ncity last night shortly before 12 o\u2019clock.\nThe Infant had been ill for several weeks\nprevious to its death. The funeral took\nplace from the family residence this aft\nernoon at 3 o\u2019clock.\nDeath of Young Boy\nBoyd Harris, a young boy 14 years of\nage, died at a local infirmary this morning\nabout 2 o\u2019clock after an illness of some\nweeks with blood poison. The boy., was\nbrought to Selma from his home at Ar\nlington about two weeks ago for treat\nment, but the disease had progressed so\nfar that medical skill could not save his\nlife, and after lingering for two weeks he\ndied early this morning. The remains\nwere carried to his former home at Ar\nlington this morning, where the inter\nment was had this afternoon.\nNEGRO FARMER\nIS DOING WELL\nFINDS READY MARKET FOR PROD\nUCTS AT EUFAUIiA\u2014OlIANO FAC\nTORY TO BE ERECTED IN BAR\nBOUR COUNTY\nEufaula, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014E<1 Lee, an\nenterprising negro who resides near Rich\nards Cross Roads, 13 miles south of the\ncity, furnishes an example of energy and\nIndustry on the farm that many of his\nrace might profit by.\nWhile In the city yesterday he disposed\nof ff quantity of home raised hams, for\nwhich he readily realised 10 cents per\npound. In addition to this he engaged\n200 pounds of home raised meat to a gro\ncery merchant here which he will deliver\nnext week and has over a hundred bush\nels ftt corn to sell. He owns 600 acres of\nland that Is unincumbered and has a well\nequipped five-horse farm In operation. He\nfurther enjoys the confidence and esteem\nof all his white neighbors and says that\nhe has no complaint to make as to his\nprospects for a good crop the coming fall.\nA guano factory for Louisville Is put\ndown as a certainty for the near future,\nand the prospects Indicate that work will\nbegin upon It at an early day. F. B.\nPearce, a prominent business man of tile\nplace, Is said to be at the head of the\nmovement which Is expected to bd In\nreadiness to supply the trade during the\nearly spring next year.\nThe old' soldiers of the county held a\nreunion at Blue Springs Thursday, where\na sumptuous feast was jenjoyed and Con\ngressman Clayton addressed the assembly\nIn a brilliant speech during the morning\nhours.\nThe contract for the erectlort of the\nBarbour county state high school has.\nbeen awarded and work Is expected to\nbegin at an early bate. The structure will\ncost about (12,000. 'and In addition 1 to the\nclassrooms and principal's office the build\ning will be equipped with an auditorium\nhaving an Inclined floor and a large, com\nmodious stage and dressing rt>oms.\n\nArmy Ordnance Inspected\nWashington, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014As a\nresult of the explbslon at Fortress Mon\nroe last week, in which a number were\nkilled, every piece qf ordnance In the\narmy Is undergoing Inspection. Tests\nare being made at all the forts, every\nsafety device on the big guns Is being\nthoroughly i overhauled.\n\nAN APPROPRIATION\nFOR OYSTER SURVEY\nMeans Much Toward Develop\nment of Alabama Beds\nWILL INCREASE AREA\nKnown Reef* Will Be Carefully Sur\nveyed and All Part* of Mobile\nBuy Will Be Sounded for\nOther Reef*\nMontgomery, July 30\u2014(Special.)\u2014A com\nmunication has been received by the de\npartment of game and fish from Con\ngressman Wash Taylor of the First con\ngressional district of Alabama notifying\nCommissioner Wallace that ap appropria\ntion was carried ii^the sundry civil bill,\npassed by the last session of Congress,\ntoward the close, sufficient In the opinion\nof the United States commissioner and\nsuperintendent of the coast and geodetic\nsurvey, to make a survey of the oyster\nbeds of Alabama.\nCongressman Taylor Informs Mr. Wal\nlace that an Independent bill which was\nurged by the state game and fish com\nmissioner, looking to this end, could not\nhave been passed at the last session of\nCongress, hence Mr. Taylor took the mat\nter up with the committee on appropria\ntion ,bf which he has been a member for\na number of years, and on which he has\nserved with a majority of the present\nmembers.\nThe First district congressman has been\nnotified by a communication from the\nUnited States bureau of fisheries that the\nbureau expects to take up the oyster\nwork In Alabama as early as possible In\nthe fall, and Is now making plans ac\ncordingly, so that no delay will ensue.\nThe intelligence contained in this com\nmunication was a cause of general rejoic\ning In the department of game and fish,\nfor In the opinion of the commissioner\nthis survey, In conjunction with Ala\nbama's new oyster law, will cut a conspic\nuous figure In developing the wonder\nful possibilities of the shellfish Industry\nIn Alabama Not only will the known\nreefs on the eastern and western Bhores\nof Mobile bay and the Mississippi sound\nbe carefully surveyed, but all parts of\nMobile bay will be sounded for the lo\ncation of oyster reefs.\nUnder the operation of the oyster law\nthat was passed at the extra session of\nthe Alabama legislature, last August,\ngreat strides have already been made In\noyster development In this state. A num\nber of factories have already been lo\ncated on Mobile bay and the oyster com\nmission has taken occasion to have re\nmoved from congested beds and reefs sur\nplus of oysters which for ages has been\npiling up, one above the other on the\nnatural rock, and have had these trans\nplanted on water bottoms suitable for\noyster culture. It Is a known fact that\nIn the warm waters of Mobile bay oysters\npropagate more rapidly and more quickly\nreach a marketable size than In any\nwaters of the United States.\nThe Alabama river and its upper tribu\ntaries traverse a limestone section, hence\nthe shell of the oysters Is easily and\nquickly fop-ned from the solution of lime\nstone that constantly flows Into Mobile\nbay. The Alabama river Is likewise per\nmeated with suitable food for oysters\nthat causes them to grow to a large size\nand to fatten early In the autumn.\nHeretofore the Alabama reefs have\nbeen looked upon as private property by\nthe oyster fishermen and have been woe\nfully vandalized, many of the most val\nuable reefs having been depleted, some\nof which have been closed to operation by\nedicts of the oyster commission, which\nis composed of John Craft, president, Mo\nbile; Daniel Bosarge, Bajiou DaBatre;\nBenjamin Patterson. Bon Secours, and\nJ. A. Joulllah, secretary, Coden.\nIt will be the purpose of the oyster\ncommission later on to prepare the water\nbottoms within the spawn circuit by the\nspreading of shell and other hard sub\nstances on which the oyster spawn can\nattach Itself. This will be a very large\nincrease in the area susceptible to oys\nter production in Alabama. The commis\nsion will also lease water bottoms be\nyond the statutory 9K>-yard riparian right\nlimit, to those wishing to engage In prac\ntical oyster culture.\nArtificial propagation of oysters has\nbeen wonderfully successful In all of the\nstates In which it has been practiced,\nfrom Virginia up the Atlantic coast line\nto Canada. On account of the vast abund\nance of oysters In Alabama It haa not\nheretofore been necessary to assist na\nture In the production of palatable bi\nvalves other than by transplanting oys\nters from the natural reefs and removing\nthem to Bon Secours bay and vicinity.\nThe cause of oyster conservation In\nAlabama was not agitated any too soon,\nbut enough oysters still remain, If prop\nerly protected and propagated, to assure\nto I he people of this state an adequate\nsupply of this excellent and nutritious\nseafood until the end of time.\nCommissioner Wallace announced today\nthat he contemplated, togethei with the\nmembers of the oyster commission, pro\nposing to the present law a number of\namendments that would greatly strength\nen It and make this statute of greater\nuse to the people.\nEXPERTS HEARD IN\nWINSTON CODNTY\nDouble Springs, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nCongressman John L. Burnett of this\ndistrict and his corps of agricultural ex\nperts and good roads men, who are mak\ning a tour of the dlstrlctf lecturing on\nup-to-date farming, stock raining and\nroad Improvement, met a large audience\nof farmers here today. Perhaps this\nwas the largest crowd gathered in Dou\nble Springs since the last term of cir\ncuit court. Representative farmers, en\nterprising farmers, who came to listen\nwere here from almost every nook and\ncorner of the county, and though the day\nwas extremely hot and the lectures last\ned far Into the afternoon, without sus\npending for dinner, these farmers kept\ntheir seats and seemed eager to hear\nevery word. Excellent address ;s were\nmade on good roads, farm demonstra\ntion and eradication of the cejtle tick\nand stock raising In general. The best\nmethod of Improving the soil and diver\nsifying the crops were discussed In detail\nby the government experts. There lec\ntures were Indeed a tnjat to the farm\ners, and Judging from the attention given\nby them maps\u2019 of them are IHcnly to\napply the methods. suggested and much,\ngood will rebuilt from the meeting of\ntoday.\nCongressman Burnett did not fail to get\nIn many good words during the lecturing,\nand did fully his part to secure all the\nInformation from the experts for the ben\nefit of Ills constituents. Mr. Biirnttt Is\nvery popular In this county,\nr Always a Good Investment\nAt Regular Prices\nJust Now They're Underpriced The most choice of\nMa.nkattan Skirls\n1.50 Quality\nIt2 00 Quality $1.38\n$2.50 Quality $1.88\n\n\nAll popular leathers\n\u2014all popular shapes j\nin new igio oxfords j\nI AH at$4.95\ni c\nCRENSHAW CLERK IS\nBEHIND JNACCOUNJS\nExaminer of Accounts Reports\nShortage to Governor\nTEACHERS\u2019 INSTITUTE\nSession In Dlrmlngham Will Begin on\nSeptember 12, Continuing Six Days.\nRailroad Commission Will\nMeet Tomorrow\nMontgomery, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Mark\nL. Black, circuit clerk of Crenshaw coun\nty, owes the state the sum of $407.77. ac\ncording to a report filed with the gover\nnor by Judge John Purlfoy, examiner of\naccounts. He was checked up on solicit\nor\u2019s fees to the extent of $1681.91, but later\npaid Into the treasury the sum of $1374.14,\nleaving him behind, on the showing made,\n$407.77. It Ib also charged by the examiner\nthat there are no records by which he\ncduld tell how much was due on fees\nheld two years, which, under the law,\nought to be turned Into the state treas\nury.\nThe examiner found that returns should\nhave been made of collections as follows:\n\"Solicitor\u2019s fees earned at the fall term\nOf the circuit court of Crenshaw county,\n1908, and should have been reported and\npaid In not later than April 30, 1909. Some\nof these fees are shown to have bean\npaid to the clerk In cash, and should have\nbeen reported and paid In December 31,\n1908.\u201d This total Is put at $638.83. Interest\n$33.63, total $694.20.\nAlso: \"Solicitor\u2019s fees earned at the\nspring term. 1909. of the Crenshaw circuit\ncourt, and which should have been report\ned and paid In not later than September\n30, 1909.\u201d This total Is. with Interest,\n$238.64.\nAlso: \"Solicitor\u2019s fees paid In at the\nfall term of the circuit court, and which\nshould have been reported and paid In\nApril 30, 1910.\u201d This'amount, with Inter\nest, Is $.702.07.\nAlso: \"The following are the fees\nearned at the spring term, 1910. of the\ncircuit court, and In the absence of execu\ntions from the clerk It Is presumed they\nwere paid, and should have been report\ned and paid Into the treasury on April 30\nlast.\u201d This total, with Interest, Is put\nat $247.\nThis makes a total on the due side of\n$1681.91. It Is noted, however, that on\nJune 23 Mr. Black paid Into the treasury\n$980.39, and on July 14. $293.78, making a\ntotal of $1274.14. leaving a balance yet\ndue by Mr. Black of $407.77, which amount\nthe governor's office has reported to tha\nstate auditor as due by the officer.\nNo record Is found by the examiner of\nfees held over two years which, under\nthe acts, should be reported Into the state\ntreasury. The examiner says: \"The\nclerk has no reoord by which the amount\nof such fees f collected and paid can be\ndetermined. There (s no data in his of\nfice by which the amounts received by\nhim and paid out can be determined.\nNeither his subpoena docket, execution\ndocket, nor fee book show this, hence I\nfound It wholly Impractical tQ check the\nwitness fees.\u201d It Is also reported by the\nexaminer that he spent much time In a\nfutile effort to determine the amount of\nsuch fees collected.\nTeachers' Institute\nThe Ninth district teachers\u2019 Institute,\nheretofore hold in Birmingham, will be\ngpllt up this year, one week going to\nOneonta. In Blount county, the other to\nBirmingham. The first dates. Oneonta,\nare August 29 to September 3. and the\nBirmingham dates September 12 to 17. The\nInstitutes In the Ninth have been of great\nvalue to and largely attended by the\nteachers, over 700 being nt Birmingham\nlast year. C. B. Glenn and C. A. Brown,\nBirmingham teachers, are to be the con\nductors. Mr. Glenn was at Montgomery\nSaturday to arrange the details.\nRnllroad Commission\nAt the meeting of the railroad commis\nsion Mondhv there will be only one case,\nthat of a movement to change the station\ncalled Kingston, on the MobITe and Ohio,\nto Spur.\nExperts at Russellville\nRussellville, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nJohn L. Burnett, member of Congress\nfrom tills district, Is here with three\nexperts sent out by the department of\nagriculture, one to leetjire on good\nroads, one on cattle, horses and hogs,\nand one on farm demonstration work.\nThrough the efforts of Mr. Burnett\nthese men have been secured for two\nweeks, and have delivered lectures In\nevery county In his district. A large\ncrowd Is In attendance today to hear\nthem, N\n\nV\nMORGAN COUNTY TOWN IS\nAn interesting old place\nBY AD LIE WEST\nHartselle, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Nestled\namong the old red hills of east Mor\ngan lies the good old town of Somer\nville. Years ago. before the onward\nmarch of progress and commercial ac\ntivity asserted itself, this old town was\nthe center of a large portion of the bus\niness, literary and social activity of the\nday for a wide area. She numbered among\nher citizens some of the foremost law\nyers, doctors, statesmen and men promi\nnent in all walks of life, as were to\nbe found anywhere. Military geniuses of\nthe day claimed her as their home, and\nthese made their impress on the history\nof the country, in time of war as well\nas in peace.\nOn a prominent bluff overlooking the\nclear waters of Town Creek still stands\nthe house that was the home of one of\nthe Confederacy\u2019s great generals. It was\nthe home of Gen. James Longstreet. Col.\nJoslah Patterson was bom and reared\nat Somerville, got his early education\nthere, later taught school In the same\nschoolhouse In which he had studied.\nWhen the war broke out he raised a\ncompany of soldiers and went to the\nfront. The old Rice homestead, where\nGov. Malcolm R. Patterson of Tennessee\nwas born, was the home of his grand\nmother. Judge S. D. Weakley, a cousin\nof Governor Patterson, was also born\nin this historic old home.\nSome of the best schools of the day\nwere taught there in the old rock school\nhouse, where so many then young men j\nwent forth to do their share in the ranks\nof good citizenship. Among the early edu\ncators of that day who were conspicuous\nin the educational advancement of that\nday, were Dr. Welch, Professor Free\nman, Professor Laken, Professor William\nK. Skeggs, the present probate judge of\nthis county. All of these taught suc\ncessful terms of school there. Profes\nsor Freeman was a northern man and\nmarried Miss Garner of this county.\nWhen the war broke out Professor Free\nman went to the front in the ranks of\nthe Confederacy^ and made a gallant\nsoldier and was promoted to the cap\ntaincy of a company.\nThe old brick courthouse, almost a cen\ntury old. is still standing, and since the\ncounty seat was moved from Somerville\nto Decatur has been used for educational\npurposes. The brick with which this old\nbuilding was constructed were made right\non the ground, as were all the other brick\nin houses that are there. Many legal\nlights of that day spent considerable\ntime at Somerville, and they were always\nglad to get to the hospitable hostelry (the\nold Stuart hotel), then run by Mrs. Jane\nFowler. Judge Clarke. Colonel Garth, S. i\nT. Wert. C. F. ftamlll, Judge Campbell.\nJudge G. P. Rice, Pope Walker and\nmany others that might be mentioned\nfigured largely in the legal work of\nthat day there.\nThe brick church erected by the old f\nblue-stocking Presbyterians still stands on.\nan eastern hill, a silent sentinel to \u2018the i\nmemory of many good men and women\nof that day. This old church is almost\na century old and is still in a fair state\nof preservation. The Presbyterians were\nthe first to get a foothold in Somerville,\nand the church has had some^very strong S\npastors and numbered a great many\nprominent people as laymen. Years ago j\nthis old church passed out of the hands\nof the Presbyterians, and for many years\nhas been used by the Baptists. The\nbrick homestead and storehouse of Wi!- j\nliam Morrow, one of the earlv merchants\nof that place. Is still standing on the\nsouth side of the square. j\nRx-Oovernnr Chapman at one time lived\nat Somerville, as did also Judge Gus\nSharpe of Birmingham. y\nSince the county seat was moved from\nSomerville much of the activity that for\nmerly prevailed there is gone, but many\nof her sons and daughters scattered all\nover the country cherish her memory,\nknowing that she has woven for herself\na wreath in memory that will live as\nlong as life itself, as she nurtured them\nin youth, and at mature age sent them\nforth well equipped for the arduous du-*\u00ab\nties that come in the battle of life.\nETOWAH FARMERS\nMORE OPTIMISTIC\nLARGEST CORN CROP IN HISTORY\nOF THE COUNTY NOW EXPECTED.\nALLEGED BLIND TIGERS ARE RE\nCENTLY RAIDED\nGadsden, July 30.\u2014(Special.)\u2014As the\nseason advances and fuller reports are\nreceived. It Is estimated that this county\nwill produce about a half average crop of\ncotton. This probably Is a fair esti\nmate for most of the north Alabama\ncounties. The corn Is coming out well\nand will make the biggest crop In the\nhistory of this section unless unfavorable\nconditions should yet beset It. Altogether\nthe farmers will be in fair financial con\ndition If the short crop will bring the\nexpected long price.\nA sensation was sprung in the city to\nday when the city and county officers\nmade a descent on some alleged blind\ntigers. The store of the Howie Bros.,\nknown aB Jhe Etowah Furniture com\npany, was closed under an Injunction Is\nsued by the register In chancery under\nthe direction of Judge J. H. Dleque. The\nplace was locked up and three men, the\nHowies and an employe, were placed un\nder arrest. No resistance was offered,\nand the men readily made bond when\ngiven the opportunity. At the same hour\na raid was made on the poolroom operated\nby H. K. Long, but no liquor was found.\nAt a conference between the city coun\ncil and the Alabama City, Gadsden and\nAttalla Railway company, held last even\ning, but little headway wus made toward\na settlement of the differences existing\nowing to a failure of the company to\nmake the improvements In Its tracks in\nthe district to be paved. The council took\nthe position that the car company must\neither get busy or give up the use of the\nstreets affected. The company meets\nthe arguments with the statement that it\nhas no money for further Improvements\nat this time, and has quit operating Its\ncars over the streets in question. The\ncouncil now threatens to tear up the\ntracks and proceed with the paving, and\nthe company stands ready to defend Its\nproperty by an appeal to the courts. The\nmatter stands as before, and the paving\ncontractor meanwhile waits to carry ou*.\n4\nhls agreement to pave the streets.\nSuperintendent T. E. Brooks of this dt> i\nvision of the Louisville and Nashvitla\nrailroad arrived in the city this morning\nand In company of an engineer Is mak\ning an Inspection of Locust street, on\nwhich the company has agreed to reduce\nthe grade. About 30 laborers have ar\nrived for the work, and this force Is ta\nbe augmented by another detachment on\nMonday morning. The work will taka\nseveral weeks.\nThe Etowah County tltgh school win\nopen for the fall term on the first Mon\nday In September. In order to stlmulata j\nInterest in the school several scholarships I\nhave been offered to be awarded under a\nsystem of competitive examinations. Tha\nscholarships are three in number and in\nclude tuition, board and room and all ex\npenses of attendance on the institution.\nThey are offered by Attatla people and\nshow the deep interest that the ettizena\nof that enterprising place are taking in\nthe school. The donors of these scholar\nships nre T. C. Banks, Dr. C. B. Fore\nman and the Attalla Industrial club.\nCHANGE\nQuit Coffee find Got Well\nA woman's coffee experience Is In\nteresting. For two weeks at a time J\nhave taken no food but skim milk, for\nsolid food would ferment and causu\nsuch distress that I could hardly\nbreathe at times, also excrutlatlng pain\nami heart palpitation and all the tiraa\nI was so nervous and restless.\n\"From childhood up I had been a\ncoffee and tea drinketpamd for the,past\n20 years I have been trying different\nphysicians but could get only tempor\nary relief. Then I read an article tell\ning how some one had been cured by\nleaving off coffee and drinking Postum\nand it seemed so pleasant Just to read\nabout good health I decided to try\nPostum In place of coffee.\nI made the change from coffee to\nPostum and such a change there is in\nme that I don't feel like the same per\nson. We all found Postum delicious and\nlike it better than coffee. My health\nnow Is wonderfully good.\n\"As soon as I made the shift from\ncoffee to Postum I got better and now\nall of my troubles are going. I am\nfleshy, my foo'd assimilates, the pres\nsure In the chest and palpitation are\nall gone, my bowels are regular, have\nno more stomach trouble and my head\naches are gone. Remember I did not\nuse medicines at all\u2014just left off cof\nfee and drank Postum steadily.\"\nRead \"The Rond* to Wellvllle,\" found\nIn pkgs. \"There's a Reason.\"\nEver reed the ehove letter? A new\none appears from time to time. They\nare genuine, true, end full of human\nInterest.","height":"28084","width":"19608"}}
